#: locations-specific.rst:225
msgid "``Ta'izz Governorate (osm, poly) 5c35b342-0b5e-4648-86cd-7ad730d647fa``"
msgstr ""

#: locations-specific.rst:230
msgid "Entries for the :ref:`location:humane_id:qa` field should combine information from several other location fields to give a researcher a quick, human readable way to understand a location. Best practice is to include the :ref:`name:annotation <location-name-annotation>`, :ref:`origin:location`, :ref:`geo_type:qa` and :ref:`id:entity` as this highlights the most important information while also creating a unique name due to the inclusion of :ref:`id:entity`. SFM adopts this approach with :ref:`location:humane_id:qa` with entries in the field following the below format:"
msgstr ""

#: locations-specific.rst:232
msgid "Example"
msgstr ""

#: locations-specific.rst:234
msgid "The value ``Ta'izz Governorate (osm, poly) 5c35b342-0b5e-4648-86cd-7ad730d647fa``, which is a combination of multiple fields: ``name:annotation`` (``origin:location``, ``geo_type:qa``) ``id:entity``, tells us that the name of the place is ``Ta'izz Governorate``, that it is a Location found in ``osm`` (short for \"OpenStreetMap\") that it denotes an area (``poly``); the UUID provides the hard link to a specific attribute in the Location table."
msgstr ""

#: locations-specific.rst:238
msgid "name:annotation"
msgstr ""

#: locations-specific.rst:244
msgid "The name of the Location as specified in the source of geospatial information from which it is taken."
msgstr ""

#: locations-specific.rst:259
msgid "``:annotation/name``"
msgstr ""

#: locations-specific.rst:264
msgid "``Ta'izz Governorate``"
msgstr ""

#: locations-specific.rst:269
msgid "The value in :ref:`name:annotation <location-name-annotation>` is to be taken directly from the geospatial data source. For example, if a Location is derived from OpenStreetMap, we take the value from OSM's own \"name\" attribute and place it in :ref:`name:annotation <location-name-annotation>`. Along with :ref:`origin_id:location` and :ref:`geo_type:qa`, :ref:`name:annotation <location-name-annotation>` is needed for automation tools to identify the object within the geospatial data source. Where a Location is arbitrarily-defined, or is derived from a data source that does not provide a name, the Staff Researcher can provide one."
msgstr ""

#: locations-specific.rst:272
msgid "origin:location"
msgstr ""

#: locations-specific.rst:278
msgid "The geospatial information source that provides information about this Location."
msgstr ""

#: locations-specific.rst:283 locations-specific.rst:317 locations-specific.rst:425 locations-specific.rst:459 locations-specific.rst:492 locations-specific.rst:528 locations-specific.rst:562 locations-specific.rst:596 locations-specific.rst:630 locations-specific.rst:664 locations-specific.rst:698 locations-specific.rst:732 locations-specific.rst:766 locations-specific.rst:800 locations-specific.rst:834 locations-specific.rst:868 locations-specific.rst:1106 locations-specific.rst:1140 locations-specific.rst:1176
msgid "String"
msgstr ""

#: locations-specific.rst:293
msgid "``:location/origin``"
msgstr ""

#: locations-specific.rst:298
msgid "``osm``, ``sfm``, ``hdx``, ``mimu``, ``khrg``"
msgstr ""

#: locations-specific.rst:303
msgid "The values in :ref:`origin:location` identify where automation tools should go to obtain spatial information about an object. For example, if the value ``osm`` is entered in :ref:`origin:location` this indicates that the automation tool should query OpenStreetMap in order to obtain spatial information about a Location. If ``osm`` were set, then the values in :ref:`name:annotation <location-name-annotation>` and :ref:`origin_id:location` would correspond to the object name and ID number in OpenStreetMap. Locations can be derived from comprehensive online services, as well as other sources like locally-held ``.shp`` or ``.kml`` files. The number of origins is unlimited."
msgstr ""

#: locations-specific.rst:306
msgid "origin_id:location"
msgstr ""

#: locations-specific.rst:312
msgid "The identifier for the Location as specified in the source of geospatial information from which it is taken."
msgstr ""

#: locations-specific.rst:327
msgid "``:location/origin-id``"
msgstr ""

#: locations-specific.rst:332
msgid "``383895``"
msgstr ""

#: locations-specific.rst:337
msgid "The value in :ref:`origin_id:location` is to be taken directly from the geospatial data source. For example, if a Location is derived from OpenStreetMap, we take the value from OSM's \"id\" attribute and place it in the :ref:`origin_id:location` attribute. Along with :ref:`name:annotation <location-name-annotation>` and :ref:`geo_type:qa`, :ref:`origin_id:location` is needed in order for automation tools to identify the object within the geospatial data source. Where a Location is arbitrarily defined, or is derived from a data source that does not provide a ID number, the Staff Researcher can provide one."
msgstr ""

#: locations-specific.rst:340
msgid "geo_type:qa"
msgstr ""

#: locations-specific.rst:346
msgid "The two-dimensional geometric primitive of the Location, as defined in the source of geospatial information from which it is taken."
msgstr ""

#: locations-specific.rst:351
msgid "Text"
msgstr ""

#: locations-specific.rst:361
msgid "``:location/geo-type``"
msgstr ""

#: locations-specific.rst:366
msgid "``point``, ``poly``, ``line``"
msgstr ""

#: locations-specific.rst:371
msgid "This attribute used a controlled vocabulary to describe the type of geometry used to represent the Location on a map. The Staff Researcher can choose from the following three options:"
msgstr ""

#: locations-specific.rst:373
msgid "``point``: the Location is a single distinct point on a map, represented by a single pair of geographic coordinates."
msgstr ""

#: locations-specific.rst:374
msgid "``poly``: the Location is a closed area on a map, its boundary described by a sequence of geographic coordinates."
msgstr ""

#: locations-specific.rst:375
msgid "``line``: the Location is a line on a map, described by a sequence of geographic coordinates. A ``line`` may also be closed."
msgstr ""

#: locations-specific.rst:377
msgid "The gazeteer used as the source of geometry may used different terminology to describe the Location. For example, in OpenStreetMap the boundaries of administrative areas (such as counties or states) `are described <https://wiki.openstreetmap.org/wiki/Relation>`_ using an object called a \"relation\"; although this can be a complex mix of different objects, for our purposes it is a ``poly`` because it describes an area."
msgstr ""

